<dl id="n08099j"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n08" href="#n08099j">N08 (VI.B.6)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n08all.htm#n08099j"> 99(j)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> present is also a sort / of vague future / remote past is always / a pluperfect</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">A notable feature of the history of the English language is the building up of a rich system of <i>tenses</i> on the basis of the few possessed by Old English, where the present was also a sort of vague future, and where the simple past was often employed as a kind of pluperfect, especially when supported by <i>oer</i>, &lsquo;ere, before&rsquo;. <small> Otto Jespersen, <a name="OJGS" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#OJGS"><cite title="source">The Growth and Structure of the English Language</cite></a>, 4th ed. (Jul 1923) 201 [Tense System]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
